segments.text: Texas A&M since 1969.
It's November the 13th, Friday.
Okay.
And I'm interviewing Dr. Shules, who has been at Texas A&M since 1969.
That's correct.
And has been in the Department of Educational Curriculum and Instruction and is still a professor here, among a lot of other things that he does.

I'd like to talk to you, Dr. Schuetz, about the major changes that you have experienced or have you been a part of since you came to Texas A&M, some of the causes that you feel might have brought about these changes.
And then we'll talk a little bit about the goals or the mission of the college.
So looking back to 1969 when you arrived, from Stanford?
No, you went?
I was in Palo Alto Unified School District.
in California.
But I did my doctoral study and master's study at Stanford.
Right.
OK. And was Dean Hubert responsible for you coming here?
Dean Hubert and Glenn Johnson.
I had somebody quote or tell me that 90% of the people that Dean Hubert had hired were still here and were still productive.
And when I wrote that up in one of my class reports,
Dr. Erlandson said, have you verified this or triangulated and make sure?
And I haven't gone through the records, and I guess I'll have to.
It might have just been something that this person just assumed or just from thinking.
I don't know if 90% was an accurate figure, but there are quite a few people in the College of Education today that were here.
In fact, all of my interviews so far have been people that were here, and it was like over 20.
And that's amazing.
And, of course, the college is not that old, but still, we're going to be hitting 20 years pretty soon.
That's right.
This is its 19th year.
And it's been tremendous fun to be in a ground floor of a whole new institution.
The College of Education was born in 1969.
The Department of Curriculum and Instruction was born in 1969.
And all of the
The structure, the precedents for the college had to be established.
That's right.

And if a person had gone to the University of Illinois or Stanford or someplace where the precedents had been 50 or 100 years old, you would have waited for 50 years to get a chance to influence something.
But those of us who came in 69 had a chance to start right in doing it.
And it was great fun.
We took on responsibilities that were more than we knew how to handle.
But we learned.
I still remember Gwen Johnson, the first year as department head.
He had so much to learn, he just couldn't do it all.
And he would stay up all night long trying to get things done.
And he would go home and take a shower and shave, come back to work at 6 o'clock in the morning.
And we just got on his case.
I told him he just couldn't do that.
But he would keep saying, I have to know these things.
I have to be responsible for these things.
I was not aware that the Department of EDCI was also born at the same time.
Tell me a little bit about how that came about.
Well, before the College of Education was born,
There was, in the College of Liberal Arts, a Department of Education.
There was, in the College of Agriculture, a Department of Agricultural Education.
There was a Department of Health and Physical Education.
I'm not sure where it was housed.
It might have been in Liberal Arts, but I don't know.
And then one in Engineering as well.
And that was Industrial Arts.
When the college came into being, the Department of Education split into educational administration, curriculum and instruction, and educational psychology.
And then after that, at the same time, industrial education moved over to education from engineering.
And after that time, we invented interdisciplinary education.
And things like adult education and vocational education somehow got added in, and educational technology got added in.
When you say we invented, what kind of process did you go through, or how did this come about?
Was it the faculty as a whole interacting with the dean to try to meet the needs at works?
How did that happen?
It wasn't the faculty as a whole.
It wasn't all the departments involved.
It wasn't all the departments in the college.
It was the ones that were particularly involved.
There were funding agencies that were asking for proposals or where there were funds available to get things started up, particularly vocational education is something that I remember.
or where there was some new development as in educational technology that one particular department, in this case, industrial education, felt was important.
So they simply tacked on to themselves this activity that didn't have a direct relationship to their ongoing traditional program.
But yes, department heads, faculty members were well involved in working with the dean, talking with the dean about such developments.
And he was always looking for ways to encourage the strengthening and attention of the application and its horizons.
There have been, and I'm going to divide this into the two distinct administrations, you know, Hubert for 10 years almost, and then now Dean Corrigan since 1980.
Were there changes in the focus of, you know, the mission is still the same, the teaching and research and the service.
Was that in equal proportion in the two eras, or has it changed any?
As far as more emphasis on either teaching or research or service?
The emphasis has changed.
I think the methodology has changed.
I think the tile of leadership has changed.
The measures of success have maybe changed.
You have to remember,
Dean Hubert came to the Deanship in Education after a preceding decade as the Dean of Liberal Arts.
And before that, the Dean of Arts and Sciences.
And so he had a view of the possible based upon considerable history of time with an institution that was pretty conservative in its outlook and its operation.

he kind of brought that into his leadership in the College of Education transcended the conservatism to the degree that he had visions of development and expansion that went way beyond what other deans would have thought about, I'm sure, in terms of the College of Education.
Corrigan came in
with a completely different set of experiences, different institutions, and things that Dean Huber would have said, no, it can't be done to.
Corrigan has said, I'm going to find out.
That's the way we used to do it in Massachusetts or Vermont or wherever he came from.
Right.
He never took no for an answer, so to speak, at the beginning of things.
He always took the more optimistic view.
And whereas Dean Hubert was insistent that we had to be getting into the research and development game with outside funding,
his measure of success was pretty much the dollars attracted.
Hubert's was?
Yes.
Okay.
And I think that's rather natural when you're beginning something.
You say, well, how are we doing?
Well, how many bucks have we got?
But as the college has matured some, I think...
faculty began to be ready to reach out in different directions and to make different kinds of proposals.
And so I think the quality of some of these activities, the originality or creativity in them has improved to some degree.
At least the diversity in them has improved.
And I don't mean saying that to disparage the work and effort of people in the first 10 years at all.
I just need to say that the critical mass got bigger and all of a sudden we were able to do things that we couldn't do before.
You mentioned the measure of success.
How is success measured now?

I think it is getting more and more to be the degree to which we influence public policy or professional points of view or the thinking, the philosophy, or the point of view within the disciplines we represent.
In other words, are we visible in our specialties nationally?
How does the college measure in that area?
Well, if you compare us in 1969 to 1989, it's day and night.
But I'm quick to say that some of the same people who were here in 1969 are the ones who are leading the way in 1989.
But they've had time to grow.
A lot of them who carried a lot of the

heavy responsibility for organization and operation and administrative roles in those years have since phased out of those and gone into other things and they have then found the time to do some research and development and writing and so on that they didn't have time to do them.
I think we have been able to attract more and more competent
already competent people.

We have actually recruited a number of people at the associate and full professor levels whose accomplishments have already been highly visible and brought them in to supplement what we were home growing as well.
And I think the combination, the mix, has been very, very successful.
I think that the college has kind of grown up in that period of time.
Its position within the university has improved steadily.
Its recognition has grown.
A number of people from the college who have served on university-wide committees and councils of one kind or another are responsible for
improving the image of education.

We've been around long enough to have served, particularly graduate faculty members, as graduate council representatives and sometimes outside members on committees in other departments, and we have earned the respect of our colleagues in those roles.
Our graduates, or let's say our students, our majors, have been improving in quality and accomplishment, and they compete effectively with other students in the university.
I remember a marvelous, marvelous event.
Well, at least a decade.
Then Vice President for Academic Affairs, John Calhoun,
noted that there were too many education majors graduating cum laude, magna cum laude, and summa cum laude, in his opinion.
He called Dean Hubert over and he said, Hubert, your standards are too low.
You got too many kids that are graduating with all these high honors.
So Hubert came back and worked with Dr. Limbacher, who was then his associate dean.
determined that the high grades these students were making were in the liberal arts and the sciences and the geosciences and not just in education.
He took that information back and shoved it under Calhoun's nose and Calhoun shut up.
It was the quality of the kids.
Not that they were being given an easy road.
And that has enhanced
our reputation around the university.
There are still people in the university that look down on people in education.
That's because, I guess, they have to look down on somebody or to feel good about themselves.
You're referring to other colleges, people in other colleges within the university.
Yes.
Anybody who is from education is automatically poorly educated,
less competent, more limited in world view, and culture, and you name it.
Are they verbal?
I mean, are they vocal about that?
Or is it just a feeling?
Oftentimes.

And it's only one in public forums, one kind or another, committees or councils, where the representative of education carries the day by the force of will and logic and precedent and argument and good persuasion that they begin to take notice and say, well, gee whiz, maybe they're not so stupid over there after all.
Well, okay, then...
You're talking a lot about collaboration and work with departments and committees.
To what extent does the College of Education, in your opinion, collaborate with, well, within the college with departments and outside of the college with other colleges?
Do you feel there's a lot, a little, or more than, I know probably more than you used to?
That's a hard one to answer, Sylvia.
I don't think we are as
You're active across departmental lines as we ought to be.
I don't know why.
We're busy.
All of us are busy.
Let me just show you.
This door has files of all the doctoral committees I'm on.
And I'm cheering now, what is it?
Looks like about 14.
And I'm serving on another
I'm on a GCR on two.
And I'm on four or five master's committees.
Is that a norm?
I mean, is that an average for this college?
Or is it something about your expertise that so many of the students want you on their committees?
Well, I think it's not evenly divided.
Not everybody in every department is so occupied with committee memberships, but a great many people are.
In your department, there are so many students and so few faculty members that by definition, they're all going to be on umpteen committees.
In this department, there are
or maybe eight or nine of us that have a heavy, heavy load of doctoral students, either as chairs or memberships.
And then some of the other specializations, there are enough people to share them fairly well.
When you take on a doctoral student, have you any idea of what the average amount of time?
I know it takes, what, a couple of years for that person to get through all the coursework and the dissertation, et cetera.
But in terms of time, I know besides the committees, I mean, the defenses and the regular meetings with all the committee, how much time does it take with each student for counseling, for review?
Those whose committees you chair takes, by definition, quite a bit of time.
Because first, you're going to do a degree plan with its contents and the committee membership.
That has to be done.
Then you're going to deal, eventually, with dissertation proposal, and that goes through several drafts, and then of course it goes through another.
There's the mind, and the chair pushes the mind, until it finally gets kind of gelled.
dissertation proper, the reviewing of chapters one at a time, that's just time consuming.
That's all it is.
And candidates come with greater or lesser degrees of competence in writing, experience in writing.
Some people have never written more than ten pages in their lives.
Tackle something that's going to be sixty to a hundred pages long.
Their sense of organization is just non-existent.
They can't think of it as an argument that starts on page one and finishes on page 99 or whatever it is.

I had one dean, one of the deans tell me that he felt that it was unfair or that it was not right to have people have that many committees, that it was a great concern of his that four or five committee
or rather graduate students should be a max, and of course there's no, that's probably not realistic, but is there talk about limiting?
We've got, in fact, a college, if not policy, at least a guideline for how many committees one should serve on.
I think there are 10 as a maximum, and serving on another 10 is exactly what it is.
I look it up periodically and I forget it.
But I have finished saying that

If just with those things, the degree plan, the proposal, and the dissertation, then you have preparation for those tests, getting the candidate aware of how it's going to go, what's going to happen, and who's going to say what.
And then there may very well be some independent study activities, some 685s.
And that takes time.
Oh, but it's nice.
The thing that's hard to predict is how much dependence the candidate will have on you.
Some of them require inordinate amounts of time.
And others do everything themselves and show you a really beautiful copy every time you see it.
That's lovely.
OK. We talked already about perceptions of outsiders, of views.
One of the things that I'm getting from everybody is a little bit about visions.
And because you've been here from the very beginning and seen how this has evolved, the visions for maybe the future of the college.
And I know right now there's some tremendous changes and upheavals, and I know or I have
sense that in this department it would have much more effect perhaps than in some of the departments are probably not going to be affected because they're just graduate students like Ed Addis.
How is that affecting the overall climate?
Well, it's unsettling.
And it remains unsettling because the rules seem to change every couple weeks.
Some kind of message out of Boston, the dean will meet with a group of observers and then they're going to respond.
And we'll get going geared up to respond that way and then new news comes out and the first response will not be adequate.
or it's in the wrong direction, or we're not sure it will be acceptable, or whatever.
It is unsettling from the standpoint that it's not clear to many of us what the target is we're trying to shoot at.
On the other hand,
it's a little bit exciting in that it's forcing a reconceived conceptualization of our whole program.
What we're doing and how we're doing it is forcing us to ask ourselves, is the traditional manner in which we've attacked the problem the best one, the only one, the most efficient one?
Might there be a better way of doing it?
Might there be a way to improve the quality of the people?
We don't have to be argued with very long.
But the broader the liberal background of the individual, the better educated he's going to be as an individual when he leaves.
And that's very good.
An elementary teacher needs to know a lot about a lot of things to be a good teacher.
Because an elementary teacher is a lot of things.
And there's nothing worse than to have somebody who teaches misinformation to children.
So it does offer some excitement.
I think that we will see probably some major changes in the next five years.
We will probably place more emphasis on graduate studies and less on undergraduate studies.
And I predict that there will be a backlash because I suspect that we will come up against a severe teacher shortage as a result of that.
Are we already facing one?
We already are facing one, yes.
And I think that what happened at the legislature as a result of the parole commission and so on was just totally wrong.
They missed the boat.
On the one hand, they're saying, you've got to teach your children, your teacher candidates, very solid content.
They've got to have good content.
That's first and foremost.
They've got to be broadly educated.
Then, they've got to know how to teach.
But especially beyond that, they've got to know how to teach reading.
They've got to know how to diagnose kids who have learning problems.
They've got to be able to handle children with special problems and needs.
And they've got to sit on ARD committees and do IEPs and so on and so on.
They've got to deal with children with cross-cultural problems and bilingual problems.
They've got to have developmental problems.
And we're only going to give you 12 hours to teach them all that.
And it can't be done.
They can't pour on more and more things that you're supposed to accomplish and give you less and less time to do it.
So they're working at cross-purposes for themselves, and they're driving the really good people in the profession up the wall.
Because we know we can't prepare somebody adequately with 12 hours, six hours of student teaching.
It just won't work.
And as we view our program, it's not really very overloaded right now with methods courses.
Probably more methods courses at the elementary level than the secondary level.
But at the secondary level, we could use more methods courses because, for instance, take somebody in mathematics.
A secondary teacher in mathematics can teach from 7th grade through 12th grade.
That means everything from remedial 7th grade math through calculus.
Now, you cannot teach somebody how to teach all of that in one semester course.
You can't do it.
You can't do it in two, for that matter.
You can do a whole course on how to teach algebra and a whole course on how to teach geometry.
And that still leaves you with the arithmetic and the remediation and the higher manner.
So some people just missed the boat on the methodology courses.
But this is political.
It always has been.
I guess it's always going to be.
It's just too bad we can't.
get a voice that keeps trying to put some sort of rationality back into the mix of things.
But I foresee that we'll move over to a five-year kind of program, pretty much.
And then we'll be forced by circumstances to move back to a four-year program.
OK.
Meanwhile, I think we're learning more and more all the time about how to teach better.
I think that the interest right now in establishing an empirical knowledge base, a research base for teacher education is very healthy.
But we don't have a research base for more than 20% of what we do.
I wrote a conference last week, or the week before, and Walter Doyle from the University of Arizona
about quite clearly that the empirical data that we've got is largely based for effective schools, effective classrooms, on skill subjects and the primary grades.
You can't generalize that to all the grades and all the subjects and all the advanced levels of understanding.
There are a lot of things like that.
So there's ferment to get at the investigation of a number of these things, and I think we'll be steadily asking better questions and answering better questions.
Is this a philosophy or a thought or a way of thinking that is different or is specified, or is it just part of its goal and its mission, just the same as it is for the college?
Does it have something different?
I kind of think it has a unique...
philosophy, undergraduate level.
Well, I don't know.
At all three levels.
I think we have tried especially hard.
And I don't know that we're unique in this, but we have tried especially hard to maintain the Aggie tradition of caring about every student, which has been very hard to do.
When I came here in 69, I knew every secondary major by name and face.
I advised every single one of them the first year I was here.
We now have something like 1,400 undergraduate majors.
And more than that, because we've got over 2,000 majors in this department, and only about 500 of them, I guess, or less, are graduate students.
So it's very hard to be personal with that many people.
And that puts a lot of strain on the people that have that philosophy but can only spread themselves so thin.
And we've been wrestling and wrestling and wrestling with the question of how to cut the numbers down so that we can do our job better and relate to our students more effectively.
But beyond that, at the graduate level, we carried a belief that there ought to be
education beneath specialization.

That is, we have at both masters and doctoral level some required core courses that people for each degree must take, regardless of whether they're going to specialize in reading or mathematics education or science education or social studies or whatever.
